[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'For 60 years, every attempt to replace silicon&nbsp; has failed. Graphene, carbon nanotubes,&nbsp;&nbsp; and dozens of other materials that were supposed&nbsp; to be the future. None of them made it. But now,&nbsp;&nbsp; for the first time, the semiconductor industry may&nbsp; have finally picked a successor. A few weeks ago,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'I was there when I presented the new chip roadmap.&nbsp; And on it, something remarkable happens. Silicon&nbsp;&nbsp; starts disappearing. not from your computer&nbsp; but from the roadmap itself. And the material&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'taking its place is just a few atoms thick. I\'m a&nbsp; chip design engineer and in this episode we will&nbsp;&nbsp; explore a new material that could replace silicon.&nbsp; The first microchip already running on it and what&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'it tells us about the future of computing.&nbsp; Subscribe to the channel and let me explain.&nbsp;&nbsp; For more than 60 years, the entire computing&nbsp; industry has been built on a single material,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'silicon. Every smartphone, every&nbsp; laptop, every AI chip. And yet,&nbsp;&nbsp; silicon was never supposed to make it this&nbsp; far. For decades, the semiconductor industry&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'was obsessed with making transistors smaller.&nbsp; And every new generation unlocked cheaper and&nbsp;&nbsp; more powerful computing. But eventually, we&nbsp; ran into something we couldn\'t shrink away.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'physics. As transistors approached atomic&nbsp; dimensions, strange quantum effects start to&nbsp;&nbsp; appear, like quantum tunneling. When electrons&nbsp; behave like waves, which means they can pass&nbsp;&nbsp; through barriers they were never supposed to&nbsp; cross. They actually started leaking into places&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'they were never meant to be. And at the same time,&nbsp; every new generation became far more expensive&nbsp;&nbsp; and far more difficult to manufacture. It looked&nbsp; like the dead end. Yet every time engineers found&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'another trick. First transistors stopped being&nbsp; flat and became finats. Then we figured that we&nbsp;&nbsp; can wrap the gate all the way around the channel&nbsp; giving us gate-all-around (GAA) architecture. And&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'honestly the result is breathtaking. You\'re&nbsp; looking at Intel\'s first 18A transistor.&nbsp;&nbsp; Those tiny horizontal bars are called nanosheets&nbsp; and they are the pathways where electrons flow.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'These are only a few dozens nanometers wide and&nbsp; they engineered to switch faster while leaking&nbsp;&nbsp; less current. But it\'s getting even crazier&nbsp; if you look underneath. Those darker lines are&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'so called Power Via. Instead of delivering&nbsp; power through the crowded top of the chip,&nbsp;&nbsp; Intel roots it from the backside. And this is&nbsp; two of the hardest problems in modern chip&nbsp;making'

[02:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'solved in the same device. You would think that&nbsp; there isn\'t much room left for new ideas. But the&nbsp;&nbsp; industry wasn\'t done. Now we are building CFETs.&nbsp; An attempt to build two transistors in the space&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'of one. Literally stacking one transistor on&nbsp; top of another. And after that comes even more&nbsp;&nbsp; stacking. If you\'ve seen my episode on China\'s&nbsp; new scaling law and chip folding, you will&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'know exactly where this story is heading. Every&nbsp; generation bought silicon a little bit more time.&nbsp;&nbsp; But eventually every trick runs out. And a couple&nbsp; of weeks ago, I was there when IMEC presented it.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'A new chip roadmap all the way beyond 2040. This&nbsp; is a roadmap. The next decade looks familiar.&nbsp;&nbsp; 2nm class chips today. Then the industry moves&nbsp; towards A7, 7 Angstrom class technology around&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: '2033 which will be a remarkable milestone. The&nbsp; first commercial introduction of CFET. But then&nbsp;&nbsp; something strange happens: around 2041 silicon&nbsp; starts disappearing not from your laptop but&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'from the transistor itself. Because after decades&nbsp; of shrinking transistors, if silicon can be made&nbsp;&nbsp; any thinner, the only option is a material that&nbsp; already is. Imagine taking a crystal and peeling&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'it apart until only a single atomic layer remains.&nbsp; That\'s the promise of 2D semiconductors. The&nbsp;&nbsp; leading candidate is a material called molybdenum&nbsp; disulfide. It\'s made from one layer of molybdenum&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'atoms sandwiched between two layers of sulfur&nbsp; atoms. just three atom layers in total. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp; before you ask, it isn\'t some exotic material.&nbsp; Molybdenum and sulfur are both relatively abundant&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'elements. And the material itself is remarkable.&nbsp; It\'s just about half a nanometer thick. The&nbsp;&nbsp; semiconductor industry has spent decades trying&nbsp; to make silicon thinner. Molybdenum starts thin.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'That is its superpower because that gives&nbsp; engineers something they desperately want,&nbsp;&nbsp; control. And the thinner the channel, the easier&nbsp; it is for the transistor gate to control the flow&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'of electrons. And better control means smaller&nbsp; and more efficient chips. Here you\'re looking at&nbsp;&nbsp; some of the world\'s first advanced 2D transistors&nbsp; built by TSMC, ASML, and IMEC. manufactured using&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'EUV lithography on a standard 300 mm wafers. In&nbsp; other words, the world\'s leading chip makers have&nbsp;&nbsp; already started building the processes to&nbsp; make it real. And with every new prototype,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the post silicon era moves a little closer. Many&nbsp; people think this is just about making transistors&nbsp;&nbsp; smaller, but it\'s not. It\'s all about power.&nbsp; When the channel is only a few atoms thick, the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'transistor gains extraordinary control over the&nbsp; electrons flowing through it and that means lower&nbsp;&nbsp; operating voltage. And in semiconductors, lower&nbsp; voltage is a huge deal. And for materials like&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Molybdenum disulfide, we are targeting roughly&nbsp; half of operating voltage of modern devices,&nbsp;&nbsp; which could translate into dramatically lower&nbsp; power consumption. Based on the published papers,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'these transistors have consumed up to a thousand&nbsp; times less energy than comparable silicon devices.&nbsp;&nbsp; And that is why this story is way bigger than&nbsp; transistor scaling. Right now, AI is pushing&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the industry into an energy crisis. Data centers&nbsp; are becoming some of the largest consumers of&nbsp;&nbsp; electricity on the planet. The industry doesn\'t&nbsp; just need more computing. It needs more computing&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'per watt. And that\'s exactly where atomically&nbsp; thin semiconductors could make a huge difference.&nbsp;&nbsp; But the story doesn\'t end there because replacing&nbsp; silicon might be not the end goal. Building on top&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'of it might be. Next, we will look at the first&nbsp; working processor built on this technology and for&nbsp;&nbsp; the first time see what a post silicon computer&nbsp; might actually look like. But before that,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'recently I\'ve been using the Anker\'s Prime&nbsp; charger, the world\'s most compact 160 watt&nbsp;&nbsp; multiport charger. And that got me thinking,&nbsp; is the original charger always the best fit?&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'When I travel, I\'m carrying two laptops, a phone,&nbsp; an iPad, camera batteries, and other accessories.&nbsp;&nbsp; Normally, that means several chargers and a mass&nbsp; of cables in my bag. The Anker Prime 160 watt&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'replaces all of that with a single charger. It has&nbsp; 3 USBC ports, so I can charge multiple devices at&nbsp;&nbsp; the same time. And if I need to power something&nbsp; demanding, like my MacBook Pro laptop, it can&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'deliver up to 140 W from a single port. What\'s&nbsp; interesting is how Anker manages to pack all that&nbsp;&nbsp; power in such a compact device. The key technology&nbsp; is based on GaN or gallium nitrite. It wastes less&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'energy as heat than traditional silicon. But&nbsp; what really matters is how Anker engineers it.&nbsp;&nbsp; With GaN Prime 2.0 and its M-Buck architecture,&nbsp; Anker reduces inductor size to one quarter of&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'traditional designs. On top of that, Power IQ 5.0&nbsp; intelligently balances power between connected&nbsp;&nbsp; devices, automatically reallocating unused wattage&nbsp; where it\'s needed most. And Active Shield 4.0&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'monitors temperature more than 10 million times&nbsp; per day to help prevent overheating. And the&nbsp;&nbsp; built-in display shows exactly how much power each&nbsp; connected device is drawing in real time. I travel&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'a lot and this one charger replaces for me a bag&nbsp; full of chargers. If you want to learn more, Anker&nbsp;&nbsp; is running \'Ask Me Anker-Thing\' series. The link&nbsp; is below. But road maps are just plans. Building a&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'working processor is something else entirely. And&nbsp; that\'s where the story gets interesting. For more&nbsp;&nbsp; than a decade, researchers were showing individual&nbsp; demonstrations, individual 2D transistors in labs.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Always the question was obvious. Can you build&nbsp; a real computer with this material? And can it&nbsp;&nbsp; run crisis? Now we have an answer. Have a look at&nbsp; this new chip from China. It\'s the world\'s most&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'advanced processor built from a 2D semiconductor.&nbsp; The chip contains 6,000 transistors, each with&nbsp;&nbsp; a channel just three atoms thick, built from&nbsp; Molybdenum disulfide. 6,000 transistors? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'at the first glance, that sounds tiny and a bit&nbsp; disappointing because a modern NVIDIA GPU like&nbsp;&nbsp; Rubin GPU contains over 300 billion transistors.&nbsp; But the legendary Intel\'s first microprocessor,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the 4004, contains just 2300 transistors. And&nbsp; unlike the 4004 whose transistors were measured&nbsp;&nbsp; in micrometers, the active material in this&nbsp; processor is only three atoms thick. But it\'s&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'a real processor built around open- source risk&nbsp; web architecture. So it can execute instructions,&nbsp;&nbsp; perform calculations, and run programs. For&nbsp; years, researchers showed individual transistors.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[10:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Now they\'re showing a working processor and&nbsp; that changes the conversation because getting&nbsp;&nbsp; one transistor to work to switch on and off is&nbsp; difficult. But getting thousands of atomically&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[10:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'thin transistors to work together is an entirely&nbsp; different challenge. When your semiconductor is&nbsp;&nbsp; only a few atoms thick, almost everything can&nbsp; go wrong. And yet they reported a yield of 99%.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[10:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'In other words, almost every transistor worked,&nbsp; which brings us to the real challenge. For years,&nbsp;&nbsp; the question was, can this atomically thin&nbsp; transistors work at all? Now, the question&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[10:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'is changed. Can this be manufactured at scale?&nbsp; Because that\'s where most silicon challengers&nbsp;&nbsp; failed. The transistor existed. The manufacturing&nbsp; process didn\'t. But that may finally starting to&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[10:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'change. One of the companies attracting a lot&nbsp; of attention in this space is CDimension. Their&nbsp;&nbsp; focus isn\'t the transistor. It\'s the material. How&nbsp; do you grow atomically thin sheets of Molybdenum&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[11:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'disulfide across an entire wafer at industrial&nbsp; scale? That turns out to be one of the hardest&nbsp;&nbsp; challenges standing between a lab and a mass&nbsp; scale manufacturing. That may sound simple, but it&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[11:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'isn\'t. Silicon has actually a 60-year head start.&nbsp; The industry knows how to grow enormous, nearly&nbsp;&nbsp; perfect silicon crystal ingots, slice them into&nbsp; wafers, and build billions of transistors on top.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[11:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'This process has been refined for years. But with&nbsp; 2D materials, we are starting from scratch. And&nbsp;&nbsp; Molybdenum disulfide isn\'t a single element. It\'s&nbsp; a compound. Every Molybdenum atom and every sulfur&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'atom has to arrive in exactly the right place at&nbsp; exactly the right time across an entire wafer.&nbsp;&nbsp; Imagine painting a football field with a brush&nbsp; just one atom wide. That\'s the level of precision&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[12:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'we are talking about. And then comes the real&nbsp; enemy, the grain boundaries. As a material grows,&nbsp;&nbsp; tiny crystals form independently. They expand&nbsp; outward. Eventually, they collide and defects&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[12:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'appear. Think of a frozen lake. Ice forms in&nbsp; different directions and where those patches meet,&nbsp;&nbsp; cracks appear. In the semiconductor, those weak&nbsp; points become defects. And for decades, silicon&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[12:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'manufacturers learned how to eliminate them. 2D&nbsp; materials haven\'t. And that\'s exactly where many&nbsp;&nbsp; promising technologies have failed before. Not&nbsp; because the transistor didn\'t work, because the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[12:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'manufacturing never did. And CDimension believes&nbsp; it has a solution and the basic idea is quite&nbsp;&nbsp; elegant. You flow gases containing molybdenum and&nbsp; sulfur across a silicon wafer. The atoms react on&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[12:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the surface and slowly assemble into a crystal&nbsp; only a few atoms thick. And the challenge here&nbsp;&nbsp; is the temperature. Because traditional methods&nbsp; require temperatures close to 1,000° C, hot enough&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[13:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'to destroy the transistors already sitting&nbsp; underneath. CDimension claims it can do the&nbsp;&nbsp; same thing at around 200 degrees, low enough that&nbsp; the silicon underneath survives, which opens the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[13:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'door to something much bigger because replacing&nbsp; silicon might be not the most interesting outcome.&nbsp;&nbsp; Building on top of it might be now for the first&nbsp; time we are touching the idea of true monolithic&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[13:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: '3D computing. You build a layer of silicon&nbsp; transistors, then a layer of 2D transistors on&nbsp;&nbsp; top, then another, and another, like constructing&nbsp; a skyscraper with entire logic layers stacked&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[13:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'vertically. And if you watched my previous&nbsp; episode about Chinese logic folding breakthrough,&nbsp;&nbsp; you\'re about to have an \'aha\' moment because these&nbsp; are not two separate stories. It\'s two different&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[14:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'attempts to solve exactly the same problem. For&nbsp; decades, the semiconductor industry improved chips&nbsp;&nbsp; by shrinking transistors and eventually it started&nbsp; running out of room. So the industry began moving&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[14:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'upward. The first step is CFET. Two transistors&nbsp; stacked on top of each other. Think of it as&nbsp;&nbsp; adding another floor to their transistor. The&nbsp; second step is what companies like Huawei and IMEC&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[14:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and TSMC are exploring by stacking logic using&nbsp; hybrid bonding. Instead of stacking transistors,&nbsp;&nbsp; you manufacture multiple silicon layers&nbsp; separately and then connect them with&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[14:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'millions of tiny vertical links. That\'s what made&nbsp; Huawei\'s result so interesting. But Monolithic 3D&nbsp;&nbsp; goes one step further. Instead of building two&nbsp; separate logic dies and stacking them together,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[14:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'you build the transistor layers directly on top&nbsp; of each other from the beginning, layer by layer&nbsp;&nbsp; inside a single chip. Basically, you have no&nbsp; bonding interface, just one monolithic 3D chip.&nbsp;&nbsp; If CFET adds another floor to the transistor and&nbsp; logic folding adds another floor to the chip. In&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[15:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'monolithic 3D approach, we are building the entire&nbsp; skyscraper tower with shorter connections and far&nbsp;&nbsp; less energy wasted moving data around. That\'s why&nbsp; Intel, TSMC, and the entire chip industry watching&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[15:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'it so closely. Not because this material is better&nbsp; than silicon, but because this is a potential path&nbsp;&nbsp; forward when traditional scaling finally runs&nbsp; out of road. And that\'s why so many researchers&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[15:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'see it as the end game. And this race is bigger&nbsp; than a single material. Today, a lot of attention&nbsp;&nbsp; goes to Molybdenum disulfide, but it isn\'t a&nbsp; single 2D material. It isn\'t running alone.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[15:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Research labs including IMEC are also looking into&nbsp; materials such as tungsten disulfide and tungsten&nbsp;&nbsp; diselenide. Think of them as members of the same&nbsp; family. Each has slightly different electrical&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[16:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'properties. Some are better at carrying electrons.&nbsp; Others are better at carrying the positive charge.&nbsp;&nbsp; But modern chips need both. So the future may not&nbsp; belong to a single material, but to a family of&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[16:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'atomically thin materials working together. If we&nbsp; look 15 years ahead, the first 2D semiconductors&nbsp;&nbsp; probably won\'t appear inside the CPU or GPU of&nbsp; your next laptop. New technology rarely arrives&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[16:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'right at the top. Usually, it earns it place step&nbsp; by step. The first commercial applications will be&nbsp;&nbsp; likely much smaller like RF switches for future&nbsp; 6G networks, photonics or MEMS devices. Because&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[16:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'these applications are easier proving grounds and&nbsp; they don\'t need billions of perfect transistors,&nbsp;&nbsp; they can benefit from the material much earlier.&nbsp; That is how many new technologies enter the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[17:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'market. first in specialized applications and only&nbsp; later at the heart of mainstream computing. It may&nbsp;&nbsp; sound slow, but the history suggests otherwise.&nbsp; Every new breakthrough in semiconductors looked&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[17:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'immature at first. Silicon photonics, superfins,&nbsp; EUV lithography, all of them spent years in what&nbsp;&nbsp; engineers call the valley of death. And yet,&nbsp; we eventually made them work. And that\'s why&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[17:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'I find this moment so fascinating because we are&nbsp; witnessing the first steps into the post silicon&nbsp;&nbsp; era. The moment the industry is seriously&nbsp; preparing for the life after silicon. If&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[17:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'you enjoyed this episode, share it with your&nbsp; friend. And now watch this one where I explain&nbsp;&nbsp; a disruptive technology which will allow us&nbsp; to shrink an AI data center to the size of a&nbsp;&nbsp; shoe box. or this one where I explain Chinese&nbsp; logic folding and a new Tau scaling law and&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[18:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'why the future of computing is vertical. Love&nbsp; you guys and I\'m going to see you there. Ciao.'
